connected_calls.note:
**Property Context**
➤ **Length of Ownership:** Owned for ~25–27 years *(implied from “must be over 25, maybe 26, 27 years now” – exact year not provided)*.
➤ **How did they come about obtaining the property:** Purchased as an investment/recreational asset ~25+ years ago *(implied; exact purchase details not provided — ask next call for more background).*
➤ **Current Use / Past Use:**
• Currently: Vacant, unimproved wooded land with standing/mature timber; preserved primarily for natural beauty and wildlife; no structures on the property.
• Past: Has had hunting leases on it before; frequently gets inquiries from people wanting to hunt there; maintained as preserved timber/recreational land rather than logging.
➤ **Frequency of Visits/Use:** Not provided — ask next call (how often he or others currently go out, especially for hunting/recreation).
➤ **Other unique/special circumstances:**
• 50-acre continuous lot (vacant land) in Floyd County; opposite side of the road from a separate 33.8-acre parcel he owns but is **not** selling.
• Property is unimproved with mature standing timber; seller has deliberately not sold to logging companies to preserve the look of the Blue Ridge Mountains.
• Elevation runs roughly from ~2,150 ft to ~2,350 ft and is south-facing; makes for very good hunting and strong wildlife habitat.
• Large neighboring tract (~600 acres) wraps around/near the 50 acres; used only for recreation/second home by a NC family, which further supports wildlife habitat and “in-nature” feel.
• Within commuting distance to Roanoke and Blacksburg (Virginia Tech); about 4–5 miles to small convenience stores; airports and full services available in those cities.

**House Details (if present)**
➤ **Bedrooms/Baths:** Not applicable — vacant land; no structures.
➤ **Square Footage:** Not applicable — vacant land.
➤ **Age:** Not applicable — vacant land.
➤ **Condition:** Land is unimproved timberland; no known development, utilities, or structures on-site; condition specifics (road access quality, internal trails/roads, etc.) not provided — ask next call.
➤ **Other Notable Improvements:** None; no structures or improvements mentioned beyond standing timber and general access from road — ask next call if any existing woods roads or cleared areas.

---

**Motivation (“Three Whys”)**
➤ **Why sell now?** It’s an asset he has held for ~25+ years; acknowledges that at some point “we liquidate our assets” and he’s willing to talk about selling now while values are strong and there is high enthusiasm for mountain land. No immediate pressure, more long-term asset liquidation.
➤ **Why haven’t they sold before?** Enjoys the Blue Ridge Mountains and the way the land looks; preserved timber instead of logging; uses it as long-term investment/recreational asset. Land values have been rising and recently strong comps, so he has held waiting for the right value.
➤ **Why not list with a realtor?** Not mentioned — ask next call. *(Currently open to investor purchase and references being “in the business” and collaborating on projects.)*
➤ **Future plans if not sold:** No urgent need to sell; will continue holding as an asset (with mature timber and recreation value) and is under no pressure — “sooner is better,” but no deadline.

---

**Decision Makers**
➤ **Primary Decision Maker:** Timothy Burke.
➤ **Other Decision Makers:** Not provided — ask next call (he occasionally says “we,” so clarify if spouse/partner or business associates also need to approve).
➤ **Decision-Making Process:** Very data and market-driven; compares to recent nearby sales (e.g., ~20 acres at just over $4,000/acre ~3 years ago and another nearby parcel at ~$10,000/acre ~1.5–2 years ago). Will review offers based on market comps and his view of strong demand for mountain land; no urgency but open to serious discussions at his price.

---

**Financials & Price**
➤ **Price Objective:** Asking **$300,000** for the 50-acre parcel (i.e., ~$6,000/acre). Basis: informal perc success, mature standing timber, recent comps of ~$4,000/acre and ~$10,000/acre nearby, strong demand for mountain land, and desirable south-facing, wildlife-rich setting. Negotiability not firmly defined, but tone suggests he’s anchored fairly strongly to $300k as justified by comps.

---

**Seller Engagement**
➤ **Response Quality:** High; corrected parcel confusion immediately, clearly described the right parcel, provided ownership timeline, pricing rationale, comps, and qualitative value points (elevation, timber, wildlife, neighboring 600 acres, access to Roanoke/Blacksburg).
➤ **Communication Style:** Professional, articulate, analytical; “in the business” and used to collaborating on land projects; calm, reasonable, and open to discussion while clearly confident in the property’s value.

---

**Qualification & Priority**
➤ **Lead Rating:**
? MEDIUM PRIORITY (Some positive indicators but mixed signals)

➤ **Justification:** Strong, high-quality property with mature timber, good recreational appeal, proximity to larger cities, and strong engagement from an experienced seller. However, price expectation is high at $300k (~$6k/acre) and he has no pressure to sell, framing it as long-term asset liquidation. Good candidate if underwriting can support near his price, but limited room for deep discounting; viability hinges on how close Synergy can get to his ask.

---

**Next Steps / Follow-Up**
➤ **Next Follow-up Scheduled:** Madeleine to call back next week around the same general time to confirm whether underwriting can meet or approach his $300k asking price (no specific date/time set; seller said he’s in and out and can return calls).
➤ **Action Items:**
• Property analysis / CMA
• Prepare initial offer range
• Research comparable sales
• Address specific concerns: Confirm exact parcel ID and boundaries of the 50-acre tract (since the 33.8-acre parcel is not for sale); quantify nearby comp sales (20-acre at just over $4k/acre and parcel at ~$10k/acre) and see how his $6k/acre ask fits; verify informal perc assumptions and any access/utility details; clarify whether any conservation/logging constraints or preferences exist.
• Other: Note strong hunting/recreational value, adjacency to ~600-acre recreational tract, south-facing slope, and proximity to Roanoke/Blacksburg in underwriting. Be prepared to discuss both investment perspective and potential exit strategies that justify/approach his $300k price point.

**Additional Notes:**
➤ 50-acre continuous, unimproved, timbered parcel in Floyd County; opposite side of the road from a separate 33.8-acre piece he is **not** selling. Informal perc test indicates it perks, but nothing is recorded with the county. Property has mature timber throughout, 2,150–2,350 ft elevation, south-facing, strong wildlife/hunting appeal, and adjacent/nearby ~600-acre recreational tract owned by an NC family. Within commuting distance of Roanoke and Blacksburg (airports, large population centers), yet still rural with the closest retail being small convenience stores ~4–5 miles away. Seller is experienced in land projects, views the parcel as a preserved asset, and is open to liquidating at what he considers fair market value (~$300k).

connected_calls.note:
**Property Context**
➤ **Length of Ownership:** Canada Creek ~20 years; Dry Hollow ~7 years.
➤ **How did they come about obtaining the property:** Not provided — ask next call. (Canada Creek was transferred into his name by his wife, but original acquisition method not discussed.)
➤ **Current Use / Past Use:**
• Currently: Rural land, mostly unused by seller; has not visited either property in over a year *(implied)*.
• Past: Not provided — ask next call (no details on prior use such as farming, hunting, timber, etc.).
➤ **Frequency of Visits/Use:** Has not been to either property in over a year; overall very infrequent visits.
➤ **Other unique/special circumstances:**
• Two parcels being sold together: ~96.8 acres on Dry Hollow Road and ~8.3 acres on Canada Creek Road.
• 8.3-acre Canada Creek parcel: Road frontage on Canada Creek Road; city water and blacktop streets; described as a “pretty good little spot” at/near “long road bridge.” No perk test done, but seller is confident it will perk.
• 96.8-acre Dry Hollow parcel: Access from a county road (Dry Hollow Road) on one side and a private road on the other, giving two entrances. Electric lines visible from the property; has a natural spring providing water.
• Area is experiencing in-migration (people moving in from California, Maine, etc.); seller believes land values are rising and will “shoot completely out of control.”

**House Details (if present)**
➤ **Bedrooms/Baths:** Not applicable — no house or structures described on either parcel.
➤ **Square Footage:** Not applicable.
➤ **Age:** Not applicable.
➤ **Condition:** Vacant land; no structure condition discussed — ask next call if any old buildings, barns, or other improvements exist.
➤ **Other Notable Improvements:** Spring on 96.8-acre tract; city water and paved road (blacktop street) on 8.3-acre tract. No other improvements mentioned — ask next call.

---

**Motivation (“Three Whys”)**
➤ **Why sell now?** Seller is 77 years old and finds it difficult to take care of everything; age and ability to manage properties are key drivers.
➤ **Why haven’t they sold before?** Believes his prices are fair and is willing to wait for the “right buyer.” Has had multiple offers over the years and has a stack of contracts but has not accepted because buyers would not meet his expectations.
➤ **Why not list with a realtor?** He is not planning to list; prefers to wait for the right direct buyer and has had many direct inquiries already.
➤ **Future plans if not sold:** Will continue to hold the properties and wait until the right person comes along at his price; confident property values will keep rising.

---

**Decision Makers**
➤ **Primary Decision Maker:** Donald Humble.
➤ **Other Decision Makers:** Spouse involved as gatekeeper/voice on initial part of call; appears supportive of his pricing stance — confirm level of decision-making authority next call.
➤ **Decision-Making Process:** Donald will think about the offer, revisit both properties (hasn’t been there in over a year), talk to a few people, review other existing offers/contracts, and then decide. Strong price anchor; will only move if he feels price is fair.

---

**Financials & Price**
➤ **Price Objective:**
• 96.8-acre Dry Hollow parcel: Wants $150,000 *(transcript garbled as “10,050,000” but context + seller’s comment that he believes it’s reasonable for the time suggests ~$150k — Unclear / ? Confirm exact number).*
• 8.3-acre Canada Creek parcel: Previously offered $50,000 by another company; he references that as a benchmark and appears to expect similar or better.
• Our offer (presented on the call): ~$100,000 total for both parcels (cash; 60–90 day close). Seller did not accept; says he needs to think about it.

---

**Seller Engagement**
➤ **Response Quality:** Good; answered questions on access, utilities, ownership length, and pricing clearly; shared context about the market and his age/limitations.
➤ **Communication Style:** Direct, old-school, and firm but polite. Very clear about his expectations and that he doesn’t want to waste anyone’s time if price isn’t met. Uses land appreciation and demand narrative to justify his stance.

---

**Qualification & Priority**
➤ **Lead Rating:**
? LOW PRIORITY (Minimal motivation or poor engagement)

➤ **Justification:** Seller is engaged and cooperative but has a strong price anchor (targeting ~150k + 50k vs our ~125k total offer) and openly states he’ll wait as long as needed for the “right buyer” as values rise. He is not in a financial bind; motivation is age/maintenance, but urgency is low. He’s unwilling to significantly discount and is content holding the properties, making a deal at our typical investment numbers unlikely in the near term.

---

**Next Steps / Follow-Up**
➤ **Next Follow-up Scheduled:** No specific date/time set. Seller invited us to check back after he’s visited the properties and thought about the offer; also open to receiving a contract by mail to review alongside his stack of other offers.
➤ **Action Items:**
• Property analysis / CMA
• Prepare initial offer range
• Research comparable sales
• Address specific concerns: Clarify his exact asking price for the 96.8-acre tract (confirm whether it is $150,000 or a different figure); confirm whether $50,000 is his firm target for the 8.3-acre tract; understand what, if anything, would make him consider a slightly lower number (timing, all-cash, quick close, etc.).
• Other:
• Mail a purchase contract and contact information to: **1959 Highway 1720, Monticello** (full city/state/ZIP to confirm in CRM).
• Note that he has **no email** and only uses his house phone; follow-up must be by phone and/or physical mail.
• When following up, ask if he has revisited the properties and whether conditions/market feedback have affected his price expectations.

**Additional Notes:**
➤ Two rural parcels: ~96.8 acres on Dry Hollow Road (county road + additional private access; two entrances; visible electric lines; spring on property) and ~8.3 acres on Canada Creek Road (city water, paved/blacktop street, good road frontage). Canada Creek tract has been owned ~20 years; Dry Hollow ~7 years. Seller’s wife transferred Canada Creek into his name, triggering the “new” sale record, but he has held it long-term. Donald is 77, finds upkeep difficult, and is “old school” (no email, only landline). He has a stack of prior offers and contracts from other buyers over the years and emphasizes that land values are climbing quickly due to in-migration. He is open to receiving our written offer but remains non-committal, wanting time to think, inspect the properties, and talk to others.

[2025-10-20 SENT] Hi Kevin, I wanted to see if you've thought about opportunities for your 172.08 acres in Newton County. - Iris, SLP

[2025-10-20 SENT] Got it. What's the least you can accept given that we will take care of all the closing costs, we will pay in cash and there will be no realtors commission?
[2025-10-20 RECEIVED] 12,000.00
[2025-10-20 SENT] Sure! Let me also get a few details from you.
Can you tell me more about this property? Is there a road access? Are utilities available? and are you aware of any easements or restrictions?
[2025-10-20 RECEIVED] It's all wooded with 3 creeks which 2 of the creeks are the property lines it's zoned A/R agricultural/ residential
[2025-10-20 SENT] Thank you for the information. You're also the sole owner, right?

[2025-10-20 SENT] Absolutely! I love that. Got it. Based on our conversation, I'd like to have our manager, Madeleine to give you a call to discuss an offer. When are you available for a quick call? Mornings or afternoons?
[2025-10-20 RECEIVED] Anytime today
[2025-10-20 SENT] Perfect. Do you also have an email address just in case?
[2025-10-20 RECEIVED] Niterider32760@live.com
[2025-10-20 SENT] Thank you! I appreciate your time. My manager will keep in touch. Have a great day!

notes.body: @Madeleine Penales@Christopher Quick his 100 acres is a development/entitlement opportunity, and he priced it accordingly. $12,000/acre is probably too high; it's got a bit of floodplain and a creek crossing. I would engage him to see how serious he is, and if there's any wiggle room on his PPA. These types of deals are time-consuming to evaluate, so I wouldn't want to invest much time into this if he's price motivated with no real urgency to sell.

notes.author: Madeleine Penales
notes.body:
Property Context
➤ Length of Ownership: ~20 years.
➤ How did they come about obtaining the property: Purchased multiple tracts at auction (two large parcels + smaller frontage parcels) to assemble a full frontage farm.
➤ Current Use / Past Use:
• Undeveloped forested land; natural springs and mature timber.
• Previously part of a paper mill farm (Bowater → Athens Land Group).
• Sold some mature pine timber; retains old oaks (80–150 yrs).
• Strong natural ecosystem, limestone springs, abundant wildlife (deer, turkey, etc.).
➤ Frequency of Visits/Use: Infrequent — regrets not spending more time there.
➤ Other unique/special circumstances:
• Two adjacent tracts: 83.5 acres + 94 acres = ~177.5 total acres in McMinn County, TN.
• Natural spring water (seller emphasizes purity via dolomitic limestone filtration).
• Extensive paved county road frontage (~1,000+ ft).
• Access via County Road 250 and abandoned county road that terminates at his gate (noted in deed).
• Secondary access via County Road 261 (possible road-to-road connection).
• Road base built up by Huber timber company — excellent foundation.
• Clear title; owned free and clear with wife (no liens, encumbrances).
• Deed states property “to enjoy and defend” — no risk of access loss per seller.
• Limestone, springs, caves nearby (adjacent property).
• Rich topography: flat pasture near road, ridge in center, flat plateau on top.
• Timber contingency: seller wishes to retain right to harvest select white oak logs (for woodworking).
House / Structure Details
➤ Structures: None currently; fully raw land.
➤ Condition: Undeveloped forest and mixed terrain (flat + ridge).
➤ Utilities: Electricity available along frontage; springs on property provide natural water; no city water hookups.
➤ Other Improvements: Roads/trails built from timber operations; strong road base from logging access.
Motivation (“Three Whys”)
➤ Why sell now? Not using the property; kids have no interest; would reinvest proceeds.
➤ Why haven’t they sold before? Enjoyed owning it; saw it as a long-term asset and retreat.
➤ Why not list with a realtor? Prefers direct transaction; dislikes listing agreements; experienced negotiator.
➤ Future plans if not sold: Continue holding; may harvest timber; not in a rush.
Decision Makers
➤ Primary Decision Maker: Darren Wirthwein.
➤ Other Decision Maker: Wife (co-owner).
➤ Decision-Making Process: Will discuss large sales directly with buyer/owner; won’t sign contingent or listing-style agreements.
Financials & Price
➤ Price Objective:
• $1,000,000 firm for both parcels together.
• Originally suggested $1.5M as “reasonable,” but would accept $1M cash, clean and quick.
• No deductions or contingencies — wants net $1M.
• Paid ~$670,000 total originally (~20 years ago).
Seller Engagement
➤ Response Quality: Extremely detailed; transparent; friendly but sophisticated.
➤ Communication Style: Intelligent, conversational, highly descriptive; professional tone.
Qualification & Priority
➤ Lead Rating:
🟢 HIGH PRIORITY (Premium property, motivated but not distressed, realistic pricing for acreage, full access, strong utility/natural water, clear title.)
➤ Justification:
• Large contiguous acreage with infrastructure, road frontage, and natural springs.
• Clean ownership & title, clear price expectations, and defined sale goal.
• Seller open to direct purchase — not seeking a listing relationship.
• High-value but straightforward acquisition opportunity.
Next Steps / Follow-Up
➤ Next Follow-up Scheduled: Next-day callback with company owner (Travis).
➤ Action Items:
• Property analysis / CMA
• Verify acreage, APNs, and parcel mapping.
• Review comps (rural estate & timberland) in McMinn County.
• Confirm deed language & access via courthouse records.
• Assess road base & slope via topo map and satellite.
• Discuss/clarify timber retention contingency.
• Prepare offer letter with clear “as-is” terms, $1M cash clean close, optional quick inspection period.
Additional Notes:
➤ Seller is a physician with extensive local knowledge; highly articulate and invested in the land’s ecological and practical features.
➤ Will cooperate and even offer property tour via ATV.
➤ Property free of debt, clean title, deed-secured access, and no restrictions.
➤ Price: firm $1M; would transfer logs before closing if needed.
➤ Prefers direct deal; no listing contracts.
➤ Excellent lead for a serious buyer — turnkey acquisition potential with exceptional natural value and accessibility.

P.S. He’s quite talkative and likes to share about his background — he’s a physician and mentioned moving from the city to Monroe, which he says makes him feel more like himself.

notes.body: Not seeing a big jump in PPA down to the 40-60 acre ranges. STR is low for 20-40. Nice looking property with road frontage, but he's fishing for a high price. If someone actually pays him $900,000 for that property, they're pretty silly IMO.

notes.author: Madeleine Penales
notes.body:
SUMMARY – Noel Deal Property (137 Acres, Candler County)
Noel (age 88) and his brother own a 137-acre multi-generational family farm with a 300 ft cell tower under lease. The property has deep emotional value — Noel was raised there, and the land has been in the family for multiple generations.
They aren’t actively trying to sell, but acknowledge they’ll need to make decisions soon due to age. Their four children are expected to benefit from the eventual sale, though it’s unclear if they are involved in current decision-making.
Key Factor: The cell tower lease heavily impacts the seller’s expectations. Noel believes the tower alone is worth “around $500,000” and “a lot more than the farm.” Our offer of $325,000 (land value only) was perceived as far too low.
The seller provided some details about the tower but little about the house or structures. He was direct and emotional on the call, emphasizing the tower's value and reacting strongly to the offer.
Motivation: Low. They plan to sell “one day,” but no timeline and strong attachment to the property. A large price gap exists between our underwriting and the seller’s expectations.
Next Steps Needed:
• Gather tower lease details (rent, renewals, ROFR, buyout, etc.)
• Clarify whether the tower lease is included or carved out in any sale
• Ask for additional property details (house, structures, condition, improvements)
• Determine if the seller has a minimum price in mind
• Set a follow-up strategy, acknowledging tower value to build credibility
Lead Rating: Low priority — low motivation, high emotional attachment, and a major valuation gap due to the tower lease.

They don't use the property and will be visiting this next week once weather clears up. They had a bad storm roll through apparently. There is a local farmer that leases the land, but he wasn't sure how much he pays. Noel is 88 and it's just him and his brother who are the decision makers. There is another interested party in the tower land and according from Noel that's what this guy buys. So FYI. We were at $315 up to 90 days and $350 for 120 days. But that was before the income producing part I. E Cell tower. Please let me know your thoughts.

notes.author: Travis Rogers
notes.body:
@Milton Hodgson flood zone properties are tricky to value. The area outside of the flood zone is 4 acres but some of that is a 500 yr flood plain which is of lower concern. I think LI AI MV of $123,947 is actually pretty close. I discounted the manual comps by -35% to adjust the price down for flood plain and that came to $117,284.

I like your suggested offer amount of $67,539.17 to start. We can go higher from there if needed, probably into the $80ks. There's a subdivide opp I could look at as well if he's looking for higher than that.

notes.author: Travis Rogers
notes.body:
@Madeleine Penales I would put this one on a 3-month follow-up. I think the lead is pretty price-motivated. This note from the lead makes them sound like a salesperson. "Timeline: Possibly raising price soon if interest rates drop"

He also said he's not open to other offers. Wouldn't waste any time trying to make an offer on this one right now. Put it in the long-term follow-up and nurture to see if he ever changes his mind or becomes more motivated.
